        <svcproc svcproctype="repair" graphiccount="0">
            <title>Service procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid property damage, personal injury, or death, park the vehicle on a flat level surface,
                        set the parking brake, turn the engine off, and chock the wheels.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Safety goggles or other adequate eye protection must be worn when working with refrigerant.
                        Serious eye injury may result from refrigerant contacting the eyes.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>For more detailed information refer to Service Manual S16025.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check for thermistor leaks with a black light or other methods.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If a thermistor or thermistor o-ring is suspected of leaking, purge the refrigerant from
                    the AC system.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the thermistor suspected of leaking and inspect the female threads and o-ring
                    sealing surface in the bore for burrs or other damage in the bore. If there are burrs or damage in
                    the bore, the component should be replaced.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect the thermistor electrical pins for corrosion. If there is corrosion, the
                    thermistor should be replaced.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the thermistor electrical pins are free of corrosion and in good condition, carefully
                    remove the o-ring being careful not to damage the thermistor. Inspect the body and threads of the
                    thermistor for burrs or damage. If there are burrs or damage, the thermistor should be replaced.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the thermistor is free of damage, install a new o-ring taking care not to twist it.
                    Apply mineral based oil, Part Number ZGGR 6912, to the o-ring before and after installation on the
                    thermistor.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Re-install the thermistor and tighten to 62 to 80 Lbf-in (7 to 9 Nm).</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Recharge the AC system with the proper amount of refrigerant and recheck the AC system
                    for leaks.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Start the vehicle and check for proper operation of the AC system.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
